FeedPackage.Description:
West Wind Globalization provides custom data driven .NET ResourceManagers and ResourceProviders for both plain .NET and ASP.NET applications as well as serving JavaScript resources from .NET resources and a rich real time Web Resource editor that can update resources live. This default implementation supports SQL Server storage for resources, with additional data providers available in separate packages.
This core package includes only core, non-Web specific features which include the custom ResourceManager implementation with support for SQL Server, support for the base database providers and support for the DbRes support class access. If you want to use ASP.NET ResourceProviders, JavaScript resources from .NET Resources, or the Web Resource Editor add the Westwind.Globalization.Web package.
For additional database providers look for the .MySql, .SqLite and .SqlServerCe versions of this package.

This library provides the ASP.NET specific components to the Westwind.Globalization library. FeedPackage.Description: West Wind Web & AJAX Utilities provide a host of AJAX and REST services for interaction with jQuery. Key features include support for easy to implement REST and AJAX services and a rich client side JavaScript library that can interact with these services easily. For WebForms there are a host of wrappers for the client side jQuery plug-in controls, or you can use them directly from script code to interact with MVC or other non-WebForm platforms. The toolkit also includes many general purpose helper classes and utility functions for low level ASP.NET operations including script loading, script compression, loading script variables into HTML output, request logging and error handling and more. Although there is some WebForms specific functionality, most of the library's generic features can be used both in WebForms and MVC as well as in handlers and modules. Note: this is the binary only distribution of the West Wind Web & Ajax Toolkit.

FeedPackage.Description:
West Wind WebSurge is an easy to use Web load testing tool that makes it easy to capture or enter a series of Web requests, and test them interactively or under automated heavy load. The goal is to make the process of creating, managing and playing back of HTTP requests easy, so you can test and re-test your sites frequently and catch performance or application issues early in the development cycle.
Use our built-in Web capture tool to capture and filter Web sessions from Web Browsers or Windows applications, use Telerik's Fiddler or manually create sessions using plain text HTTP headers in a text file. All HTTP request data is stored as plain HTTP headers, so it's easy to create, edit or generate test sessions manually of via code.
Capture HTML requests, AJAX, REST and SOAP services. Capture SSL requests, provide POST data and custom headers - anything HTTP supports you can use in your session. Once captured play back the session under load by running for a specified time and number of simultaneous sessions. See summarized results, a few simple graphs and examine individual requests and failures. Finally a command line tool is available to automate load tests from the command prompt or with shell scripts.
FeedPackage.ReleaseNotes: This update changes to more lenient licensing. Adds the ability to test all requests in a session once for easy review in non-load scenarios. Time to 1st byte is now captured. .websurge extension support for session files so they just open in WebSurge when clicked. Optional formatted view with Syntax coloring for HTML, JSON and XML results.
FeedPackage.Summary: Quick and easy HTTP Request and HTTP Load Testing for your Web Applications
FeedPackage.Tags: load-testing stress-testing web-test rest url-test capture test replay-http test-http

FeedPackage.Description:
Wetnap is a series of helper methods that make coding in .NET a bit easier. For example, instead of if !string.IsNullOrEmpty(foo), you can write foo.HasChars(). It has a bunch of other string helpers, like foo.After("http://"), etc.
It also has a few cool methods like a For that acts just like jQuery's for function.
The goal is to make code a bit more concise, which adds up to a lot in the end. BTW, it's called wetnap because it's a nice luxury to have, just like a wet nap after a plate of hot wings.
FeedPackage.Summary: Wetnap is a series of extension methods that make coding in .NET a bit easier, especially with strings.
